title: Auburn dismisses receiver D'haquille Williams - AL.com
text:
Auburn dismisses receiver D'haquille Williams San Jose State vs. Auburn San Jose State defensive tackle Travis Miller (63) runs after Auburn wide receiver D'haquille Williams (1) during the first half Saturday, Oct. 3, 2015, at Jordan-Hare Stadium in Auburn, Ala. (Julie Bennett/jbennett@al.com) (JULIE BENNETT) Comments 
Auburn receiver D'haquille Williams has been dismissed from the football team. 
Auburn coach Gus Malzahn made the announcement Monday night, but did not cite a specific reason for the senior's dismissal. 
"When individuals fail to meet the expectations of our program, there has to be consequences," Malzahn said in a statement. "I gave D'haquille the chance to prove himself. I am disappointed that it did not work out." 
A reason for the dismissal was not provided Monday night. 
Williams had only 12 catches for 147 yards and one touchdown through the first five games of the season. He entered the season a top-round draft prospect, but now his future beyond Auburn is in doubt. 
The senior had a history of off-the-field troubles before and after his arrival on the Plains in 2014. He was suspended for the Outback Bowl after violating unspecified team rules -- and after a photo of himself with a black eye was uncovered on Instagram. 
Coaches suspended him again in August for more "discipline issues." He was allowed to return to practices six days later. 
Williams was a breakout star in 2014. He caught 45 passes for 730 yards and five touchdowns despite missing three games, including two due to a knee injury. 
ESPN analyst Mel Kiper Jr. rated Williams the nation's No. 1 draft-eligible receiver in the offseason . 
"Duke is a guy that had an opportunity to be a first-round pick," receivers coach Dameyune Craig said in the spring. "He chose to come back. He didn't come back to be a fourth receiver, to be fighting for a job, we understand that."
